            "creation_date": 1366669484,
            "body": "<p>This should get you moving in the right direction: In Java, we <code>extend<\/code> classes and <code>implement<\/code> interfaces.<\/p>\n",
            "answer_id": 16157775,
            "question_id": 16157736
        },
        {
            "owner": {
                "profile_image": "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/f87a659d1d01c81bd340c09f181eb90b?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG",
                "account_id": 26084,
                "user_type": "registered",
                "user_id": 67598,
                "link": "https://stackoverflow.com/users/67598/digitaljoel",
                "reputation": 26644,
                "display_name": "digitaljoel",
                "accept_rate": 79
            },
            "content_license": "CC BY-SA 3.0",
            "score": 2,
            "is_accepted": true,
            "last_activity_date": 1366686912,
            "creation_date": 1366669572,
            "body": "<p>Issues I see in what you have so far:<\/p>\n\n<ul>\n<li>In Java, an <code>interface<\/code>'s methods are all <code>public abstract<\/code> so they don't need to be declared as such.<\/li>\n<li>A Java <code>class<\/code> can extend another <code>class<\/code> or <code>abstract class<\/code> but implements an <code>interface<\/code>. So in your case, your Guitar should implement the Tuner class, and would contain an implementation of the methods that are declared in the interface that it implements, in this case, the <code>tune<\/code> method.<\/li>\n<li>The <code>main<\/code> method is the entry point into the application, and your application should only need one of these.  Then, within that method you would create an instance of a <code>Guitar<\/code> and an instance of a <code>Radio<\/code> and call the <code>tune<\/code> method on each of those instantiated objects.<\/li>\n<\/ul>\n",
            "answer_id": 16157790,
            "question_id": 16157736,
            "last_edit_date": 1366686912
        },
        {
            "owner": {
                "profile_image": "https://i.sstatic.net/R8AYO.jpg?s=256",
                "account_id": 2366187,
                "user_type": "registered",
                "user_id": 2071828,
                "link": "https://stackoverflow.com/users/2071828/boris-the-spider",
                "reputation": 61396,
                "display_name": "Boris the Spider",
                "accept_rate": 88
            },
            "content_license": "CC BY-SA 3.0",
            "score": 0,
            "is_accepted": false,
            "last_activity_date": 1366669637,
            "creation_date": 1366669637,
            "body": "<ol>\n<li><code>interface<\/code>s do not have <code>abstract<\/code> methods - all methods are abstract by definition.<\/li>\n<li>All members of an <code>interface<\/code> are <code>public<\/code> by default - you do not need the <code>public<\/code>.<\/li>\n<li>You implement an <code>interface<\/code> and extend a <code>class<\/code>. You need to <code>implements Tuner<\/code>.<\/li>\n<li>The <code>implements Tune<\/code> is just superfluous. <\/li>\n<\/ol>\n",
            "answer_id": 16157803,
            "question_id": 16157736
        }
